<div id="content">

    
        	    





		
										

        


                
                	    

    
                





<ul class="article-attributes trackable-component b4" data-component="Article:byline">
	        		<li class="byline">
							        	<div class="contributor-full">
        
		Staff and agencies	</div>
					</li>
		<li class="article-attributes-social-buttons"></li>
	

	
          <li class="publication">
			<a itemprop="publisher" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20131220154213/http://www.theguardian.com/">theguardian.com</a>,
				            <time itemprop="datePublished" datetime="2005-01-05T07:23EST" pubdate>Wednesday 5 January 2005 07.23 EST</time>	        
        </li>
			

	
	</ul>
    
        	    





		
										

        


    
        

        <div id="article-wrapper" class="trackable-component " data-component="Article:in body link">

        	
        			<div id="main-content-picture" itemscope itemprop="image" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject">
							<img src="https://web.archive.org/web/20131220154213im_/http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Football/Pix/pictures/2005/01/04/linogetbig.jpg" width="128" height="128" alt="Assistant referee Ray Lewis" itemprop="contentUrl representativeOfPage" data-pin-description="Rob Lewis: Into the eye of the storm"/>
										<div class="caption" itemprop="caption">Rob Lewis: Into the eye of the storm</div>
					</div>
	

    
    <div id="article-body-blocks">
	    <p>Fifa today dismissed calls for video evidence to prevent mistakes such as the one that cost Tottenham victory at Old Trafford last night.</p><p>However, football's governing body have already organised to trial inserting a micro-chip inside the ball next month, and if the test is considered successful the micro-chipped ball will be used in the Carling Cup final at Cardiff's Millennium Stadium the following day, on February 27.</p><p>Pedro Mendes's goal against Manchester United was disallowed despite the ball being clearly over the goal-line, but today Fifa's director of communications Markus Siegler opposition to the rules of the game.</p><p>"Fifa is strongly against the use of video evidence to decide the referees' decisions," he said.</p><p>"The only thing that could be considered is the technology to decide whether the ball has crossed the line or not if - and so far it is not the case - a suitable technological solution is found.</p><p>"We just have to accept the decision last night of the referee and his assistant. There is no point arguing about that. It's part of football."</p><p>Last night, Mendes's 50-yard shot at goal was fumbled by Manchester United goalkeeper Roy Carroll, who hurriedly scrambled to paw the ball back into the field of play, with the match still scoreless.</p><p>Referee Mark Clattenburg and his assistant Ray Lewis both missed the ball crossing the line by a metre, and rival mangers Sir Alex Ferguson and Martin Jol were both in agreement afterwards that video technology should be used in the future.</p><p>Today, the Football Association issued a statement outlining their tentative support for such a proposal, seemingly placing them at odds with Fifa. The statement read: "The FA is willing to discuss and consider any form of goal-line technology that would improve decision-making while not disrupting the game."</p><p>They were supported by the Scottish Football Association, with their spokesman adding: "We are certainly keen to modernise the game where possible. The specifics of goal-line technology will be discussed at the next meeting of the International FA board at the end of February.</p><p>"We obviously recognise that, as technology improves and is being introduced to other areas of the game such as new forms of turf, there is the possibility to change the laws of the game.  But there are a wide range of issues to be considered as to exactly how that should be done."</p><p>German ball manufacturers adidas are due to make a presentation to the International Football Association Board in Cardiff on February 26, pointing out the benefits of a ball with a micro-chip that bleeps once it has fully crossed the goal-line. But the Football League's own sponsorship contract with Mitre means a conflict of interest would in all likelihood prevent the adidas ball being used.</p><p>Siegler acknowledged that the matter will be raised at the IFAB meeting, but said that new technology would have to be used on a trial basis first and that it was highly unlikely any change to the laws of the game would be made this year.</p><p>"There is one annual meeting of the board every year," he said. "Only at this meeting can any changes to the laws of the game be decided.</p><p>"I do not think that after one presentation or one technology (trial) that a very quick decision will be taken because this is a crucial matter."</p>
    </div>

    

		
		
            	    





		
										

        

			            						
					
					
                                                                                                                                                                                                                            

                                                                        
	
	
		
			
                                                        
